<i>cash prize ever, $50,000.</i>

00:29.112 --> 00:36.203
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:37.579 --> 00:39.665
<i>‐ I'm boatswain mate</i>
<i>first class Jerad Clymer,</i>

00:39.665 --> 00:40.874
<i>29 years old.</i>

00:40.874 --> 00:42.042
<i>I love making knives.</i>

00:42.042 --> 00:43.544
It's a good way to
relieve stress.

00:43.544 --> 00:45.462
<i>If I were to win</i>
<i>Battle of Branches,</i>

00:45.462 --> 00:46.880
<i>it will help me set up</i>
<i>my shop</i>

00:46.880 --> 00:48.632
<i>to take on bladesmithing</i>
<i>full time,</i>

00:48.632 --> 00:50.384
<i>'cause I don't have no</i>
<i>fancy, nice tools.</i>

00:50.384 --> 00:52.970
So I'm gonna fight
as hard as I can.

00:52.970 --> 00:54.388
<i>‐ My name is Lee Crawford.</i>

00:54.388 --> 00:56.723
<i>I was an operations specialist</i>
<i>second class in the navy.</i>

00:56.723 --> 00:58.600
I was in a bad accident in 2015

00:58.600 --> 01:00.269
where I was burnt over 30%
of my body.

01:00.269 --> 01:04.022
<i>I was diagnosed with PTSD</i>
<i>and an aversion to fire</i>

01:04.022 --> 01:05.399
that I had to overcome,

01:05.399 --> 01:07.401
and bladesmithing
helped me do that.

01:07.401 --> 01:10.112
<i>‐ I'm Fire Controlman Chief</i>
<i>Petty Officer Tyler Northcutt,</i>

01:10.112 --> 01:11.738
<i>and I'm 28 years old.</i>

01:11.738 --> 01:13.615
I got into making knives
when I was a child.

01:13.615 --> 01:15.742
My father made knives
when he was a kid.

01:15.742 --> 01:18.078
<i>It'd be a great honor</i>
<i>to represent the navy</i>

01:18.078 --> 01:19.371
<i>in the Battle of the Branches</i>

01:19.371 --> 01:21.748
to just prove that the navy
does do everything better

01:21.748 --> 01:23.667
than all the other branches.

01:23.667 --> 01:25.419
<i>‐ My name is</i>
<i>Lieutenant Elijah Waddle.</i>

01:25.419 --> 01:26.920
<i>I'm an officer in</i>
<i>the United States Navy,</i>

01:26.920 --> 01:28.130
<i>and that's what I will</i>
<i>always do</i>

01:28.130 --> 01:30.591
until they retire me
kicking and screaming.

01:30.591 --> 01:33.093
<i>People that know me</i>
<i>describe me as</i>

01:33.093 --> 01:34.428
"the nicest guy
you'll ever meet."

01:34.428 --> 01:36.179
<i>I'm just a big cuddly</i>
<i>teddy bear.</i>

01:36.179 --> 01:37.139
[laughs]

01:37.139 --> 01:38.265
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:38.265 --> 01:39.975
‐ Sailors,
welcome to The Forge.

01:39.975 --> 01:41.435
Today we continue with

01:41.435 --> 01:43.937
our Battle of the Branches
competition

01:43.937 --> 01:45.647
with you sailors from the navy

01:45.647 --> 01:49.443
battling for the right
to occupy the navy's anvil

01:49.443 --> 01:51.987
in our Battle of the Branches
final competition,

01:51.987 --> 01:55.782
with the winner receiving
a check for $50,000, gentlemen.

01:55.782 --> 01:56.950
‐ [chuckles]

01:56.950 --> 01:58.827
‐ Let's go ahead and meet
your judges now.

01:58.827 --> 02:01.163
Up first, two‐time
"Forged in Fire" champion

02:01.163 --> 02:02.289
Ben Abbott.

02:02.289 --> 02:04.666
Next, historic weapons
re‐creation specialist

02:04.666 --> 02:05.792
David Baker.

02:05.792 --> 02:08.879
And last, Kali martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

02:08.879 --> 02:11.006
Gentlemen,
making a signature blade

02:11.006 --> 02:13.258
in your signature style,
man, that's a piece of cake

02:13.258 --> 02:14.176
at this point.

02:14.176 --> 02:15.218
We're not doing that.

02:15.218 --> 02:17.554
Instead, you'll be making...

02:17.554 --> 02:20.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:20.682 --> 02:22.851
One of these.

02:22.851 --> 02:25.896
That is a Mark 3 dive tool
or dive knife.

02:25.896 --> 02:27.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:27.147 --> 02:30.359
<i>The Mark 3 dive knife is</i>
<i>a compact multi‐purpose blade</i>

02:30.359 --> 02:32.110
<i>that has been</i>
<i>the standard issue tool</i>

02:32.110 --> 02:35.155
<i>for U. S. special naval</i>
<i>forces for over 30 years.</i>

02:35.155 --> 02:36.490
<i>The blade features</i>
<i>a clip point</i>

02:36.490 --> 02:38.784
<i>and a long row of serrated</i>
<i>teeth on the back</i>

02:38.784 --> 02:40.827
<i>that were ideal for</i>
<i>sawing through thick rope,</i>

02:40.827 --> 02:42.996
<i>especially when underwater.</i>

02:42.996 --> 02:44.998
<i>An all‐purpose weapon,</i>
<i>it was built to withstand</i>

02:44.998 --> 02:48.835
<i>the harsh corrosive conditions</i>
<i>of working on the sea.</i>

02:48.835 --> 02:51.338
<i>You must have a clip point,</i>

02:51.338 --> 02:55.342
<i>a sharpened false edge,</i>
<i>3 inches of saw back,</i>

02:55.342 --> 02:56.843
<i>and a through tang.</i>

02:56.843 --> 02:58.220
<i>The length of your blade</i>
<i>should be</i>

02:58.220 --> 03:00.847
<i>between 8 and 10 inches.</i>

03:00.847 --> 03:02.724
<i>‐ Making this</i>
<i>Mark 3 dive knife</i>

03:02.724 --> 03:04.142
is absolutely
a crazy challenge.

03:04.142 --> 03:06.687
<i>We have to meet a bunch of</i>
<i>different parameters.</i>

03:06.687 --> 03:08.355
<i>There's a lot of room</i>
<i>for error,</i>

03:08.355 --> 03:10.857
and a lot of ways that
you can screw this one up.

03:10.857 --> 03:14.277
‐ So, what are you gonna be
making these knives out of?

03:14.277 --> 03:17.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:17.406 --> 03:18.699
<i>Anchor chain.</i>

03:18.699 --> 03:20.492
<i>You'll have to combine</i>
<i>anchor chain</i>

03:20.492 --> 03:24.162
<i>with some 10‐series steel</i>
<i>in a San Mai technique</i>

03:24.162 --> 03:25.872
<i>to forge your Mark 3s.</i>

03:25.872 --> 03:27.916
<i>‐ Never done San Mai</i>
<i>successfully.</i>

03:27.916 --> 03:31.044
I tried it once,
and it was a catastrophe.

03:31.044 --> 03:34.714
So it's gonna be a challenge.

03:34.714 --> 03:36.675
‐ Gentlemen, you'll have
three hours in which

03:36.675 --> 03:37.801
to complete all this work.

03:37.801 --> 03:39.719
In the second round,
you'll attach handles to

03:39.719 --> 03:41.054
your Mark 3s,
turning them into

03:41.054 --> 03:42.264
fully functional dive tools.

03:42.264 --> 03:44.975
They will be tested for
strength and durability

03:44.975 --> 03:47.018
in an anchor chain chop...

03:47.018 --> 03:48.311
and for edge retention in

03:48.311 --> 03:51.565
a Kevlar‐reinforced
sandbag slice.

03:51.565 --> 03:53.483
Failure to meet a single one
of the parameters

03:53.483 --> 03:55.569
is grounds for immediate
dismissal from The Forge

03:55.569 --> 03:57.237
with no deliberation.

03:57.237 --> 03:59.239
You're military guys‐‐
you understand

03:59.239 --> 04:01.700
there's a standard
that you gotta hit.

04:01.700 --> 04:03.410
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:03.410 --> 04:05.912
Your three hours starts...now.

04:05.912 --> 04:08.748
<i>[metal rock music]</i>

04:08.748 --> 04:10.584
‐ All right, guys.
‐ All right, grab the torches.

04:10.584 --> 04:12.085
[indistinct chatter]

04:12.085 --> 04:13.837
‐ Yep.
‐ This is one piece, right?

04:13.837 --> 04:14.754
‐ Yeah.

04:14.754 --> 04:16.423
‐ Dave, in harvesting
these links,

04:16.423 --> 04:18.091
how do you think that
these guys should go

04:18.091 --> 04:19.092
with the challenge?

04:19.092 --> 04:20.260
<i>‐ Take that link,</i>

04:20.260 --> 04:22.095
<i>just cut the side of it off,</i>

04:22.095 --> 04:23.972
<i>flatten that into</i>
<i>1/4‐inch piece.</i>

04:23.972 --> 04:25.599
<i>And it's almost gonna be</i>
<i>the same size</i>

04:25.599 --> 04:26.767
as that piece of the 95.

04:26.767 --> 04:30.645
‐ So two chains, two spines
welded to that 1095

04:30.645 --> 04:32.647
and then San Mai
forged together.

04:32.647 --> 04:35.817
‐ Anchor chain,
it's not hardenable metal,

04:35.817 --> 04:37.277
but it's a strong metal,

04:37.277 --> 04:39.446
<i>so I grabbed</i>
<i>the acetylene torch.</i>

04:39.446 --> 04:41.448
<i>I know it's fast,</i>
<i>I know how to use it,</i>

04:41.448 --> 04:43.950
and I can probably,
without wasting too much time,

04:43.950 --> 04:46.036
<i>chop up enough pieces</i>
<i>for everybody to use.</i>

04:46.036 --> 04:47.245
Come on.

04:47.245 --> 04:50.207
‐ We've got Lee going at
this chain link with a torch.

04:50.207 --> 04:52.793
And then over in the other side
of The Forge,

04:52.793 --> 04:54.961
all the other competitors,
you know,

04:54.961 --> 04:57.798
kinda welding up
their 10‐series steel.

04:57.798 --> 05:01.134
‐ I'll cut 'em up and be done
with it and move on.

05:01.134 --> 05:03.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:03.970 --> 05:05.472
‐ I'm comfortable with
the San Mai.

05:05.472 --> 05:08.642
<i>Downside is making it</i>
<i>out of this piece of chain.</i>

05:08.642 --> 05:10.685
‐ What is Jerad doing
over there, man?

05:10.685 --> 05:12.145
Is he just trying to
straighten out

05:12.145 --> 05:13.146
that link over there?

05:13.146 --> 05:14.648
‐ Yeah, and he's got that
work stick on it,

05:14.648 --> 05:16.775
which I think he might have
thought would make

05:16.775 --> 05:18.735
a good leverage
until it gets really hot.

05:18.735 --> 05:21.488
At which point, it just bends
easier than the chain.

05:21.488 --> 05:23.490
<i>‐ The process I'm doing</i>
<i>right now is I'm trying to get</i>

05:23.490 --> 05:25.408
the 1095 smashed down,

05:25.408 --> 05:27.619
get these two mild steels
on each side of it

05:27.619 --> 05:29.496
and start making the shape
raise profile.

05:29.496 --> 05:31.373
[machine whirring]

05:31.373 --> 05:33.041
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

05:33.041 --> 05:34.584
<i>‐ I've used a Mark 3 before,</i>

05:34.584 --> 05:38.171
<i>but that's all the experience</i>
<i>I have with a knife like this.</i>

05:38.171 --> 05:39.172
<i>Never made one,</i>

05:39.172 --> 05:41.508
but it's about the attitude
you have.

05:41.508 --> 05:43.718
I'm here to have fun.
I'm having fun.

05:43.718 --> 05:46.638
‐ Elijah over here,
he basically got it

05:46.638 --> 05:47.681
mostly straight.

05:47.681 --> 05:49.474
Went right to the press,
went squish.

05:49.474 --> 05:52.018
‐ Yep.
‐ Smart move.

05:52.018 --> 05:53.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:53.311 --> 05:57.190
‐ All of our smiths have
traditional layered San Mai.

05:57.190 --> 05:59.568
‐ Yeah, the mild‐‐high carbon
mild.

05:59.568 --> 06:00.485
[tool buzzes]

06:00.485 --> 06:02.195
<i>‐ As far as I know about</i>
<i>San Mai,</i>

06:02.195 --> 06:04.364
<i>it's a‐‐you know‐‐a high</i>
<i>carbon piece of steel</i>

06:04.364 --> 06:06.199
<i>sandwiched between either</i>
<i>a Taco</i>

06:06.199 --> 06:08.034
<i>or just flat on top of</i>
<i>each other</i>

06:08.034 --> 06:10.203
<i>of two mild pieces of steel.</i>

06:10.203 --> 06:13.039
I got my 1095 all smashed out
and flat.

06:13.039 --> 06:15.375
Plan is to take
two anchor chains,

06:15.375 --> 06:17.627
make kind of a sandwich
method, Damascus,

06:17.627 --> 06:20.714
and then pound that out
and make the knife after that.

06:20.714 --> 06:22.716
<i>I gotta make</i>
<i>a big ol' sandwich,</i>

06:22.716 --> 06:25.218
that way they'll weld up
a little bit better.

06:25.218 --> 06:27.429
<i>Now I'm just gonna clean 'em</i>
<i>up as fast as possible.</i>

06:27.429 --> 06:29.806
[groans]
<i>You don't want all that grime</i>

06:29.806 --> 06:32.392
and dust and dirt
that's from forging 'em out

06:32.392 --> 06:34.561
<i>to go into your knife itself,</i>
<i>and then those'll create</i>

06:34.561 --> 06:36.730
<i>inclusions and delam</i>
<i>and all that.</i>

06:36.730 --> 06:39.566
So I wanna make sure
they're nice and clean.

06:39.566 --> 06:43.737
‐ Forge welding is about
85 to 90% preparation.

06:43.737 --> 06:45.739
<i>You get everything clean.</i>

06:45.739 --> 06:48.241
<i>You get everything MIG welded</i>
<i>so it doesn't slide and move.</i>

06:48.241 --> 06:49.826
You get much more success...
‐ That's the big one, yeah.

06:49.826 --> 06:51.328
‐ Than if you
just kind of wing it.

06:51.328 --> 06:53.246
‐ Get hot faster.

06:53.246 --> 06:56.124
‐ Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed.

06:56.124 --> 06:59.586
You have two hours remaining
to finish your Mark 3s.

06:59.586 --> 07:00.920
‐ Hell yeah!

07:00.920 --> 07:02.255
<i>‐ Everything's ready to go.</i>

07:02.255 --> 07:04.424
<i>I want to make three pieces</i>
<i>of steel</i>

07:04.424 --> 07:06.426
look like one piece of steel.

07:06.426 --> 07:08.261
<i>I've never used this kind of</i>
<i>welder before,</i>

07:08.261 --> 07:10.722
<i>and just stopped working</i>
<i>on me.</i>

07:10.722 --> 07:11.765
<i>The clock is ticking.</i>

07:11.765 --> 07:13.767
I started freaking out
a little bit.

07:13.767 --> 07:16.436
<i>So I do</i>
<i>my boatswain mate thing.</i>

07:16.436 --> 07:17.604
<i>I mean,</i>
<i>it's just kind of like</i>

07:17.604 --> 07:19.064
<i>the reputation we have</i>
<i>in the navy,</i>

07:19.064 --> 07:21.107
you know, just hit something
till it works, and...

07:21.107 --> 07:22.484
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:22.484 --> 07:25.654
And it worked.
[laughs]

07:25.654 --> 07:28.615
<i>It's time to do</i>
<i>some forge welding.</i>

07:28.615 --> 07:30.116
<i>‐ So, I got my three pieces</i>
<i>of metal.</i>

07:30.116 --> 07:32.202
They're clean, smooth,
black, flush...

07:32.202 --> 07:36.122
and finally it's hot enough
to get my forge weld done.

07:36.122 --> 07:38.792
‐ Lee's preparation was
the cleanest I've seen.

07:38.792 --> 07:39.793
‐ Yep.

07:39.793 --> 07:41.044
‐ Each one of those
pieces of steel

07:41.044 --> 07:42.295
was matched up beautifully.

07:42.295 --> 07:45.632
Just set his welds on big blue,
looks beautiful.

07:45.632 --> 07:49.886
‐ The next thing I need to do
is get my tip hammered in.

07:49.886 --> 07:51.513
‐ Getting that
clip point right...

07:51.513 --> 07:53.223
you can always take
a rectangular bar

07:53.223 --> 07:54.474
and grind a clip point on.

07:54.474 --> 07:56.768
But to forge it in
takes a little pre‐work.

07:56.768 --> 07:58.812
<i>You want parallel sides</i>

07:58.812 --> 08:02.524
<i>and then a demarcation‐‐a knee</i>
<i>where that starts to drop off.</i>

08:02.524 --> 08:05.610
<i>‐ I like to hammer</i>
<i>and use the anvil.</i>

08:05.610 --> 08:07.153
<i>This is where the form</i>
<i>is coming from,</i>

08:07.153 --> 08:09.114
<i>this is what is gonna</i>
<i>determine</i>

08:09.114 --> 08:12.492
whether you have
a butcher knife

08:12.492 --> 08:14.035
or a machete.

08:14.035 --> 08:17.247
‐ So, hammering this tip in
is really stressful

08:17.247 --> 08:18.498
on those welds.

08:18.498 --> 08:20.834
It's much more gentle
on the welds to cut that tip

08:20.834 --> 08:24.087
and then just forge the tip,
then you forge the bevel in.

08:24.087 --> 08:26.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:26.047 --> 08:28.550
<i>‐ When I'm shaping</i>
<i>this knife out, the only thing</i>

08:28.550 --> 08:31.553
in my head is parameters‐‐
making sure I meet 'em.

08:31.553 --> 08:34.848
<i>So I'm constantly looking at</i>
<i>the knife on display</i>

08:34.848 --> 08:37.016
to make sure
I got the profile correct.

08:37.016 --> 08:40.395
‐ Jerad's already got
what looks like a tang

08:40.395 --> 08:41.938
and a dip worked in there.

08:41.938 --> 08:43.732
<i>‐ I think navy's gonna do good</i>
<i>in this competition,</i>

08:43.732 --> 08:45.650
'cause they're ain't
no crayons out there

08:45.650 --> 08:47.527
for the army or marines,
and they're ain't no

08:47.527 --> 08:49.279
<i>golf clubs for the air force.</i>

08:49.279 --> 08:50.238
[laughs]

08:50.238 --> 08:53.241
‐ Bladesmiths!
90 minutes has elapsed!

08:53.241 --> 08:55.744
That is half the time
in this round!

08:55.744 --> 08:57.370
‐ Nice.
Very nice.

08:57.370 --> 08:59.706
<i>‐ I got the forge weld set.</i>
<i>Everything looks good.</i>

08:59.706 --> 09:01.124
This is the first time
I ever used

09:01.124 --> 09:03.710
a power hammer before,
and this thing is just amazing.

09:03.710 --> 09:05.879
<i>It's pushing metal so fast.</i>

09:05.879 --> 09:08.214
‐ Tyler's billet is looking
kind of lean, it's‐‐

09:08.214 --> 09:10.425
‐ It's looking lean,
but it's solid.

09:10.425 --> 09:11.551
‐ Yeah, yeah.
Sure.

09:11.551 --> 09:14.429
I hope he just gets
out of blue hypnosis

09:14.429 --> 09:16.139
and into knife making.

09:16.139 --> 09:17.891
‐ This thing's getting
a little long here.

09:17.891 --> 09:19.100
20 inches.

09:19.100 --> 09:21.394
You know, it's way too long,
way too thin.

09:21.394 --> 09:23.897
<i>So now I'm gonna have to</i>
<i>reduce the length of the blade</i>

09:23.897 --> 09:26.733
by half and also increase the
thickness by twice as much.

09:26.733 --> 09:28.568
Probably should have
cleaned these up.

09:28.568 --> 09:30.070
That way if I make it
to the next round

09:30.070 --> 09:31.071
and do a anchor chop,

09:31.071 --> 09:33.239
<i>I can actually survive</i>
<i>the test.</i>

09:33.239 --> 09:34.908
So now I'm gonna try
to get this thing

09:34.908 --> 09:37.077
in one solid piece.

09:37.077 --> 09:38.745
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

09:38.745 --> 09:40.288
<i>‐ I cut off the end of</i>
<i>my billet...</i>

09:40.288 --> 09:41.289
Perfect.

09:41.289 --> 09:42.874
Everything is solid.

09:42.874 --> 09:45.210
<i>And then I go to weld on</i>
<i>a piece of rebar</i>

09:45.210 --> 09:46.419
<i>to use as a handle...</i>

09:46.419 --> 09:48.296
[bleep]!
Oh.

09:48.296 --> 09:49.547
And it's hot.

09:49.547 --> 09:51.091
Oh, boy.

09:51.091 --> 09:53.843
So I got a nice
little burn on my hand.

09:53.843 --> 09:54.969
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:54.969 --> 09:57.597
‐ Oh, yeah.
He cooked himself good.

09:57.597 --> 09:59.140
‐ Yeah.
‐ Yeah, I got a glove.

09:59.140 --> 10:01.226
‐ It's just another obstacle

10:01.226 --> 10:03.186
in an already difficult
competition.

10:03.186 --> 10:05.438
‐ Yeah.
‐ Ah, [bleep].

10:05.438 --> 10:06.815
‐ Hot steel.

10:06.815 --> 10:08.942
So I'm running around trying
to get these welds set...

10:08.942 --> 10:10.110
[bleep].

10:10.110 --> 10:12.612
And I see this big ol' split
right down the middle.

10:12.612 --> 10:14.656
‐ That thing completely
delaminated.

10:14.656 --> 10:15.949
‐ Kinda freaking out.

10:15.949 --> 10:17.742
Stress is kinda mounting
a little bit.

10:17.742 --> 10:18.993
[bleep].

10:18.993 --> 10:21.121
<i>Nothing seems to be</i>
<i>welding up.</i>

10:21.121 --> 10:22.914
And I'm like,
"Ah, holy crap.

10:22.914 --> 10:25.083
<i>This is a catastrophic</i>
<i>failure for me."</i>

10:25.083 --> 10:26.960
‐ There's no coming back
from that, not at this time.

10:26.960 --> 10:29.254
<i>‐ Might not be able</i>
<i>to even get a blade done</i>

10:29.254 --> 10:30.296
<i>at this point.</i>

10:33.550 --> 10:34.926
<i>‐ When I was first in</i>
<i>the navy,</i>

10:34.926 --> 10:37.303
my first ship motto was
"never give in,"

10:37.303 --> 10:40.140
and I apply that to
everything I do.

10:40.140 --> 10:42.100
<i>I still have time left,</i>
<i>so I'm gonna go over,</i>

10:42.100 --> 10:44.352
re‐weld it up and see if I can
get these welds to stick.

10:44.352 --> 10:45.812
‐ Bladesmiths!

10:45.812 --> 10:48.064
You have 60 minutes remaining!

10:48.064 --> 10:49.607
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:49.607 --> 10:51.651
<i>‐ Got the blade within</i>
<i>the parameters.</i>

10:51.651 --> 10:53.778
About ready to quench.

10:53.778 --> 10:56.739
There's no tings,
there's no cracks.

10:56.739 --> 10:58.158
<i>Now that I have</i>
<i>a hardened blade,</i>

10:58.158 --> 11:01.744
I need to put the saw back on
and just clean it up.

11:01.744 --> 11:04.497
‐ They gotta be careful of
the sharp angles that

11:04.497 --> 11:06.457
they leave in the spine,
because that can be

11:06.457 --> 11:09.169
a weak point if
not done properly.

11:09.169 --> 11:11.171
‐ Solid teeth on it.

11:11.171 --> 11:14.174
Now I'm just gonna try to
clean it up as best I can.

11:14.174 --> 11:17.260
<i>‐ There are countless ways</i>
<i>to put these saw teeth in.</i>

11:17.260 --> 11:19.846
I am going to do it
the fastest,

11:19.846 --> 11:21.598
most efficient way I know how.

11:21.598 --> 11:23.516
<i>As I cut in</i>
<i>the saw tooth blade</i>

11:23.516 --> 11:25.935
<i>and I pull back,</i>
<i>I let that grinding wheel</i>

11:25.935 --> 11:28.146
<i>curve off the top of</i>
<i>last tooth I've done.</i>

11:28.146 --> 11:29.439
<i>Then I cut the next tooth.</i>

11:29.439 --> 11:32.192
‐ He's putting those teeth on
before the quench.

11:32.192 --> 11:35.028
‐ But all those teeth become
stress points

11:35.028 --> 11:36.529
during the quench.

11:36.529 --> 11:38.364
‐ Each one of those teeny
little tips

11:38.364 --> 11:41.367
is gonna get really hot,
so allow the stress to happen

11:41.367 --> 11:43.620
on that solid blade,
that solid billet

11:43.620 --> 11:45.747
with as much metal
as you can there.

11:45.747 --> 11:47.957
Then cut those in,
as opposed to allowing

11:47.957 --> 11:50.418
that stress to happen
when you created

11:50.418 --> 11:52.629
all these possible
stress points.

11:52.629 --> 11:55.632
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

11:55.632 --> 11:57.258
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:57.258 --> 11:58.968
<i>‐ It's got a little bit</i>
<i>of a kick to it,</i>

11:58.968 --> 12:01.554
but that's something I think
I'll completely grind down.

12:01.554 --> 12:03.306
‐ Lee seems to have
a pretty good grasp on

12:03.306 --> 12:04.974
what he's doing.
What do you think?

12:04.974 --> 12:06.893
‐ Lee is making
a drop point knife.

12:06.893 --> 12:08.019
‐ A drop point knife?

12:08.019 --> 12:10.146
‐ There's no clip on
Lee's blade right now.

12:10.146 --> 12:12.607
‐ Hopefully,
he'll grind that in.

12:12.607 --> 12:14.525
‐ Wicked, wicked, wicked.

12:14.525 --> 12:17.278
<i>‐ I start grinding in</i>
<i>my false edge,</i>

12:17.278 --> 12:19.197
and then I remember,
"Oh, wait.

12:19.197 --> 12:21.658
I have to put saw teeth
in this thing.

12:21.658 --> 12:23.910
<i>I've never done</i>
<i>a saw back before,</i>

12:23.910 --> 12:27.247
but it's actually working
really, really well.

12:29.332 --> 12:31.417
‐ Tyler's profile looks
really good.

12:31.417 --> 12:32.835
If those forge welds are good,

12:32.835 --> 12:34.796
I think he's got
a good design.

12:34.796 --> 12:36.381
‐ Yeah.
<i>‐ So right now I'm just</i>

12:36.381 --> 12:39.133
<i>rushing as best I can</i>
<i>putting saw teeth in.</i>

12:39.133 --> 12:42.011
I've never put saw teeth
into a blade before.

12:42.011 --> 12:43.596
<i>So hopefully,</i>
<i>I can get this done</i>

12:43.596 --> 12:46.349
and at least meet
what they're looking for.

12:46.349 --> 12:47.976
‐ Oh, my God.

12:47.976 --> 12:50.478
‐ Well, what he's doing is,
he's cutting pyramids.

12:50.478 --> 12:51.771
Those aren't saw teeth.

12:51.771 --> 12:54.691
Saw teeth point
either one way or the other.

12:54.691 --> 12:56.359
‐ Not the prettiest thing
in the world,

12:56.359 --> 12:58.444
but, my God, that'll do.

12:58.444 --> 13:00.113
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

13:00.113 --> 13:02.740
<i>‐ I need to get this blade</i>
<i>heat‐treated.</i>

13:02.740 --> 13:06.035
So, heat it up,
put it in the oil...

13:06.035 --> 13:08.621
I file test it.
I've got a hard edge.

13:08.621 --> 13:10.957
‐ 15 minutes, bladesmiths!

13:10.957 --> 13:12.208
<i>‐ I'm running out of time,</i>

13:12.208 --> 13:14.711
<i>really worried about</i>
<i>the quench.</i>

13:14.711 --> 13:16.671
If anything happens...

13:16.671 --> 13:18.131
<i>it'll be over for me.</i>

13:18.131 --> 13:19.424
It looks pretty straight.

13:19.424 --> 13:22.051
<i>It sounds hard, so hopefully</i>
<i>it'll survive the tests.</i>

13:22.051 --> 13:27.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:27.890 --> 13:29.809
‐ Elijah just got that
J‐flux 220 on flat platen,

13:29.809 --> 13:31.602
and he's gonna bear into it
with his knife.

13:31.602 --> 13:34.731
And I think those things
pop at the seam so easily.

13:34.731 --> 13:36.566
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:36.566 --> 13:38.901
‐ Boom!
Called it.

13:38.901 --> 13:40.486
[laughter]

13:40.486 --> 13:45.283
‐ Five, four, three, two, one.

13:45.283 --> 13:47.869
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools!

13:47.869 --> 13:50.496
This first round of
competition is over.

13:50.496 --> 13:52.415
Good job.

13:52.415 --> 13:53.666
‐ Whoo!

13:53.666 --> 13:55.501
<i>‐ There was times out there</i>
<i>on The Forge floor</i>

13:55.501 --> 13:57.295
<i>that I was thinking,</i>
<i>"I'm not gonna be able to</i>

13:57.295 --> 13:58.546
<i>finish this blade."</i>

13:58.546 --> 14:00.256
<i>It's not the best looking</i>
<i>thing in the world,</i>

14:00.256 --> 14:02.175
<i>but I'm just super proud</i>
<i>of myself</i>

14:02.175 --> 14:03.259
just turning in a knife.

14:03.259 --> 14:05.386
It was a huge accomplishment.

14:05.386 --> 14:06.345
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

14:06.345 --> 14:07.680
In this first round of
competition,

14:07.680 --> 14:10.516
we asked you guys to use
a San Mai technique to

14:10.516 --> 14:13.561
make for us a Mark 3 dive tool.

14:13.561 --> 14:15.980
And now the judges wanna see
how you did.

14:15.980 --> 14:17.106
Jerad, you're up first.

14:17.106 --> 14:19.108
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:19.108 --> 14:20.693
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:20.693 --> 14:23.196
<i>‐ Well, Jerad, first thing</i>
<i>I notice is</i>

14:23.196 --> 14:24.447
it's really thick.

14:24.447 --> 14:26.783
I would have liked to see
a lot more

14:26.783 --> 14:28.910
hammering on here,
giving it more of

14:28.910 --> 14:30.411
the dimension like
the original.

14:30.411 --> 14:33.247
I like that you do have
a straight back

14:33.247 --> 14:34.290
to a clip point.

14:34.290 --> 14:37.043
I mean, it's a solid piece.

14:37.043 --> 14:38.211
‐ All right, Lee.
You're up.

14:38.211 --> 14:40.463
Present your blade
to the judges.

14:40.463 --> 14:42.048
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:42.048 --> 14:45.009
<i>‐ All right, Lee, first up,</i>
<i>good job on your San Mai.</i>

14:45.009 --> 14:46.052
<i>It is clean.</i>

14:46.052 --> 14:49.222
<i>You see how it's just</i>
<i>one solid piece.</i>

14:49.222 --> 14:51.432
<i>What I see is also</i>
<i>your saw back here,</i>

14:51.432 --> 14:52.809
<i>nice and clean.</i>

14:52.809 --> 14:56.020
What I do not see
is that clip.

14:56.020 --> 14:57.313
<i>‐ Yes, sir.</i>

14:57.313 --> 15:01.275
‐ So if you do move forward,
that's what we're asking for.

15:01.275 --> 15:02.443
‐ Understood.

15:02.443 --> 15:03.861
‐ All right, Elijah.
You're up.

15:03.861 --> 15:05.738
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:05.738 --> 15:08.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:08.908 --> 15:10.660
<i>‐ Your clip kinda goes,</i>

15:10.660 --> 15:11.911
<i>"Oh, I'm gonna be</i>
<i>a long clip.</i>

15:11.911 --> 15:13.496
<i>Oh, no I'm gonna be a short‐‐"</i>
<i>you know.</i>

15:13.496 --> 15:16.082
So you got multiple things
going on in here,

15:16.082 --> 15:18.334
as opposed to that
straight profile

15:18.334 --> 15:19.710
and then drop to the point.

15:19.710 --> 15:21.671
<i>This delam, you know,</i>
<i>I'm hoping that</i>

15:21.671 --> 15:24.048
<i>that's just an edge delam</i>
<i>and that</i>

15:24.048 --> 15:26.592
that weld is solid in here.

15:26.592 --> 15:27.593
I like it.

15:27.593 --> 15:30.805
It just needs a lot of
basic refinement.

15:30.805 --> 15:32.056
‐ All right, Tyler.
You're up.

15:32.056 --> 15:33.683
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:33.683 --> 15:35.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:35.017 --> 15:36.727
<i>‐ Well, Tyler,</i>
<i>I like that you have</i>

15:36.727 --> 15:38.646
<i>a nice clip point in here,</i>

15:38.646 --> 15:40.815
but this knife
just isn't welded.

15:40.815 --> 15:42.567
I mean...
[hollow tapping]

15:42.567 --> 15:44.026
That's not a...
[tapping continues]

15:44.026 --> 15:46.779
a sound of a solid piece
of metal right there.

15:46.779 --> 15:50.449
I can actually see
all the way through

15:50.449 --> 15:52.118
<i>the crack in your blade.</i>

15:52.118 --> 15:55.788
Yeah, there's just no way
around this failed weld here.

15:55.788 --> 15:58.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:58.583 --> 15:59.584
‐ All right, bladesmiths.

15:59.584 --> 16:01.627
It's time for one of you
to set sail.

16:01.627 --> 16:04.046
The seaman leaving
The Forge is...

16:04.046 --> 16:07.466
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

16:07.466 --> 16:08.801
Tyler.
‐ [clicks tongue]

16:08.801 --> 16:10.386
‐ Your blade didn't make
the cut.

16:10.386 --> 16:12.263
Doug Marcaida's gonna
tell you why.

16:12.263 --> 16:15.892
‐ Tyler, we literally can see
right through your blade,

16:15.892 --> 16:18.060
which makes us question
the structural integrity

16:18.060 --> 16:20.062
of your weapon.

16:20.062 --> 16:22.773
‐ Tyler, please surrender
your blade.

16:22.773 --> 16:25.568
<i>‐ No regrets that I have.</i>
<i>It was a great experience.</i>

16:25.568 --> 16:27.528
I may not be the Battle of
the Branches champion,

16:27.528 --> 16:29.447
but one of my fellow brothers
in the navy

16:29.447 --> 16:30.573
<i>definitely will be.</i>

16:30.573 --> 16:32.325
<i>Good luck out there,</i>
<i>and I hope you beat</i>

16:32.325 --> 16:34.243
the other branches
and come out on top,

16:34.243 --> 16:35.578
as the navy always does,

16:35.578 --> 16:40.082
<i>not just in bladesmithing,</i>
<i>but you know, in general.</i>

16:40.082 --> 16:41.083
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

16:41.083 --> 16:42.627
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:42.627 --> 16:44.086
You've made it into
the second round

16:44.086 --> 16:45.171
of this competition.

16:45.171 --> 16:46.589
Now that those blades
have been tempered,

16:46.589 --> 16:48.674
it's time to turn them into
fully functional

16:48.674 --> 16:52.011
Mark 3 knives by attaching
handles to them.

16:52.011 --> 16:53.846
<i>You must have</i>
<i>a symmetrical crossguard,</i>

16:53.846 --> 16:57.099
<i>a stacked rubber handle,</i>
<i>and a butt cap,</i>

16:57.099 --> 16:58.935
as well as an acid etch.

16:58.935 --> 17:01.437
Gentlemen, you'll only have
two hours in this round

17:01.437 --> 17:03.898
to complete your handles
and get all of

17:03.898 --> 17:05.775
the flaws and issues that
were identified

17:05.775 --> 17:07.526
in your blades hammered out.

17:07.526 --> 17:09.654
At the end of this round
your blades will be tested for

17:09.654 --> 17:13.282
strength and durability
in an anchor chain chop

17:13.282 --> 17:14.450
and for edge‐retention

17:14.450 --> 17:17.286
in a Kevlar‐reinforced
sandbag slice.

17:17.286 --> 17:18.454
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:18.454 --> 17:21.123
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts now.

17:21.123 --> 17:22.541
<i>[metal rock music]</i>

17:22.541 --> 17:24.126
‐ Lee is still standing there.

17:24.126 --> 17:25.211
‐ Really?

17:25.211 --> 17:26.837
<i>I'm still trying to process</i>
<i>"two hours,"</i>

17:26.837 --> 17:27.797
<i>and it's ready, set, go.</i>

17:27.797 --> 17:29.799
And I'm like, "Two hours"?

17:29.799 --> 17:30.883
I thought he was joking.

17:30.883 --> 17:32.301
[both laugh]
‐ Me too.

17:32.301 --> 17:35.555
‐ This is a very difficult
amount of work to do

17:35.555 --> 17:37.098
in two hours.

17:37.098 --> 17:39.058
<i>‐ My clip point that</i>
<i>I thought was a clip point</i>

17:39.058 --> 17:41.018
<i>was actually just</i>
<i>a drop point</i>

17:41.018 --> 17:42.687
<i>with a false edge.</i>

17:42.687 --> 17:46.232
‐ Lee's steel is nice.
The welds are beautiful.

17:46.232 --> 17:49.652
Grinding out in the profile,
it's just the wrong shape.

17:49.652 --> 17:51.904
<i>‐ I wanna be behind</i>
<i>the navy anvil</i>

17:51.904 --> 17:55.324
to represent the navy
and all other navy personnel

17:55.324 --> 17:57.743
that have the courage
to step into

17:57.743 --> 18:00.913
the blacksmith shop
and do something different.

18:00.913 --> 18:02.290
Okay.

18:02.290 --> 18:04.292
‐ Means a lot to me
being one step closer

18:04.292 --> 18:05.501
to representing the navy.

18:05.501 --> 18:07.003
<i>I'm going to try and take</i>
<i>some of the meat</i>

18:07.003 --> 18:08.212
<i>out of this blade.</i>

18:08.212 --> 18:10.548
‐ He could knock half of
the width of that blade off

18:10.548 --> 18:14.260
and make it a lot closer
looking to what the example is.

18:14.260 --> 18:16.887
‐ Coming into this round,
I'm exhausted.

18:16.887 --> 18:19.682
I'm gonna need another pair.
I've already ripped these.

18:19.682 --> 18:23.019
<i>My hand is injured,</i>
<i>so I'm coming into this</i>

18:23.019 --> 18:25.521
already a little worn down.

18:25.521 --> 18:28.316
But I'm navy.
Adversity is part of the job.

18:28.316 --> 18:30.818
‐ I can imagine what
Elijah's going through‐‐

18:30.818 --> 18:32.903
The fact that he's blistered
all his fingers,

18:32.903 --> 18:34.447
and having to grind,

18:34.447 --> 18:37.116
and the heat
travelling into that.

18:37.116 --> 18:39.785
‐ I started chasing that
delamination,

18:39.785 --> 18:41.704
<i>but it's not going anywhere.</i>

18:41.704 --> 18:43.706
‐ Dave, would it be worth
running a beaded weld

18:43.706 --> 18:45.082
down the length of that
delamination?

18:45.082 --> 18:46.292
‐ I look over there
and I see that chain

18:46.292 --> 18:48.544
and I think,
"Yeah, maybe it would be."

18:48.544 --> 18:50.046
[laughter]
‐ I know, right?

18:50.046 --> 18:52.298
<i>‐ I take a look at it,</i>
<i>it's not going anywhere.</i>

18:52.298 --> 18:53.466
So I'm just gonna leave it.

18:53.466 --> 18:55.134
<i>I need to get started on</i>
<i>this handle.</i>

18:55.134 --> 18:57.553
<i>I've only got two hours.</i>

18:57.553 --> 18:59.388
<i>‐ I get all my chunks</i>
<i>sliced up.</i>

18:59.388 --> 19:01.057
I'm stacking 'em,
I'm kinda eyeballing

19:01.057 --> 19:02.308
about how long
my handle has to be

19:02.308 --> 19:04.810
and five‐minute epoxy
between each layer.

19:04.810 --> 19:06.437
‐ Lee's handle
is getting a little long

19:06.437 --> 19:07.772
and out of control, I think.
‐ Yeah.

19:07.772 --> 19:11.359
‐ Lee's got a 5,
5 1/2‐inch‐tall handle.

19:11.359 --> 19:13.277
<i>‐ I get the butt cap on.</i>

19:13.277 --> 19:15.446
I tap it down,
get it nice and snug,

19:15.446 --> 19:17.406
and I do a cold peen.

19:17.406 --> 19:18.491
<i>You gotta be slower with it,</i>

19:18.491 --> 19:20.159
<i>but you're not pulling</i>
<i>any temper</i>

19:20.159 --> 19:22.036
<i>or introducing heat</i>
<i>into the glue</i>

19:22.036 --> 19:25.748
or the rubber or any melt‐able
materials in the handle.

19:25.748 --> 19:27.083
<i>The time is ticking down.</i>

19:27.083 --> 19:30.878
I gotta shape this giant
rubber handle.

19:30.878 --> 19:33.255
‐ Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed.

19:33.255 --> 19:34.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:34.382 --> 19:36.050
‐ [bleep].
<i>As I'm working on</i>

19:36.050 --> 19:39.512
a material for my guard,
my hand is slowing me down.

19:39.512 --> 19:42.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:42.640 --> 19:44.975
Having one hand
is really inconvenient.

19:44.975 --> 19:46.435
‐ I feel sorry for you,
brother.

19:46.435 --> 19:49.021
‐ As I'm clamping everything
together,

19:49.021 --> 19:51.857
<i>I'm squeezing the butt cap</i>
<i>and the guard together,</i>

19:51.857 --> 19:54.860
and I pull the guard off
of the ricasso.

19:54.860 --> 19:57.446
<i>My five‐minute epoxy</i>
<i>is setting up</i>

19:57.446 --> 20:00.574
and gluing the rubber
to my tang,

20:00.574 --> 20:04.620
and I've got a nice little gap
right where my guard is.

20:04.620 --> 20:05.871
[bleep].

20:05.871 --> 20:07.123
‐ You want that guard
to be solid.

20:07.123 --> 20:08.499
You don't want the guard
to be able to

20:08.499 --> 20:10.626
float with the handle material.

20:10.626 --> 20:11.961
<i>‐ I gotta try</i>
<i>and get this thing</i>

20:11.961 --> 20:16.465
into a shape that will fit
into a human's hand.

20:16.465 --> 20:18.968
<i>I'm just getting frustrated.</i>

20:18.968 --> 20:21.637
I'm going to try and fix it,
if I have time.

20:21.637 --> 20:23.723
If not, it's gonna be
a wobbly guard,

20:23.723 --> 20:25.641
<i>and it's gonna be what it is.</i>

20:25.641 --> 20:27.268
Well, that sucks.

20:27.268 --> 20:30.396
‐ I have never done
a stacked rubber handle before.

20:30.396 --> 20:33.441
What I'm gonna do is,
I'm gonna try and burn it on.

20:33.441 --> 20:34.734
<i>In my mind I'm thinking,</i>

20:34.734 --> 20:36.318
"It's just gonna melt
right on through.

20:36.318 --> 20:38.320
It's gonna be a perfect fit."

20:38.320 --> 20:40.489
‐ Would you do a burn through?
‐ No.

20:40.489 --> 20:43.784
I think it's the slowest way
I could imagine ever trying.

20:43.784 --> 20:45.411
<i>[energetic rock music]</i>

20:45.411 --> 20:48.205
‐ The only problem I'd have
with a burn through is

20:48.205 --> 20:51.250
is some rubbers just evaporate
away from heat.

20:51.250 --> 20:54.128
‐ The MAPP gas I don't think
is getting the tang hot enough

20:54.128 --> 20:55.671
to where I need it to be.

20:55.671 --> 20:58.340
So I go get
the oxy‐acetylene torch

20:58.340 --> 21:00.593
<i>and I get the tang really hot.</i>

21:00.593 --> 21:04.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:04.096 --> 21:05.848
<i>I'm pushing down with</i>
<i>all my might,</i>

21:05.848 --> 21:08.017
and these things are still not
going through.

21:08.017 --> 21:09.393
<i>[dramatic chords]</i>

21:09.393 --> 21:11.771
<i>I don't know if this rubber</i>
<i>is like, fire‐retardant.</i>

21:11.771 --> 21:14.106
I don't know if it's 'cause
I don't know what I'm doing.

21:14.106 --> 21:17.067
‐ All of these stumbling blocks
can really throw you.

21:17.067 --> 21:19.195
<i>‐ But time is ticking.</i>
<i>I don't know if I'll be able</i>

21:19.195 --> 21:20.196
<i>to finish this up in time.</i>

21:24.116 --> 21:27.077
Ah, damn it.
‐ You have just 30 minutes
remaining to finish your work!

21:27.077 --> 21:29.705
<i>‐ I got the handle to where</i>
<i>I'm comfortable with it.</i>

21:29.705 --> 21:30.998
Everything feels nice
and tight.

21:30.998 --> 21:33.125
‐ That's a very long handle.

21:33.125 --> 21:35.419
‐ Now it's moving on
to the finishing.

21:35.419 --> 21:37.296
<i>And I still have to</i>
<i>acid etch it</i>

21:37.296 --> 21:39.089
and get it all cleaned up.

21:39.089 --> 21:41.425
<i>I'm feeling really good</i>
<i>right now.</i>

21:41.425 --> 21:43.636
‐ Jerad, he's got a clamp
on both sides

21:43.636 --> 21:45.888
pulling the butt cap
towards the guard.

21:45.888 --> 21:47.640
‐ We've talked about
these rubber handles

21:47.640 --> 21:49.558
and how important that
compression is.

21:49.558 --> 21:51.811
You really have to get that
tightened down

21:51.811 --> 21:54.146
or else that rubber's
going to shift.

21:54.146 --> 21:56.524
<i>‐ It's time to weld that</i>
<i>butt cap on.</i>

21:56.524 --> 21:59.318
<i>‐ I get it to shape</i>
<i>roughly a handle,</i>

21:59.318 --> 22:02.154
but I still gotta get some kind
of edge on this thing.

22:02.154 --> 22:06.158
I want this thing to actually
be able to cut something.

22:06.158 --> 22:08.828
‐ I'm hoping that Elijah
remembers to etch his blade,

22:08.828 --> 22:11.956
because where the line between
the high carbon steel

22:11.956 --> 22:14.667
and this jacket steel is
is important.

22:14.667 --> 22:17.837
‐ At least know that he doesn't
have any of that soft steel

22:17.837 --> 22:19.630
up on his edge.

22:19.630 --> 22:21.507
‐ I don't if I'm gonna be
able to make it.

22:21.507 --> 22:23.008
<i>[tense music]</i>

22:23.008 --> 22:25.803
‐ Ten seconds to get it
all knocked out!

22:25.803 --> 22:27.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:27.471 --> 22:32.351
Five, four, three, two, one!

22:32.351 --> 22:35.521
This second round of
competition is over.

22:35.521 --> 22:36.814
‐ Oh, you like that?
Ooh.

22:36.814 --> 22:40.192
‐ Bladesmiths, please secure
your 8 to 10‐inch

22:40.192 --> 22:43.112
acid‐etched Mark 3 blades,

22:43.112 --> 22:44.905
and stand behind your anvils,
gentlemen.

22:44.905 --> 22:47.283
‐ I'm still worried about
that edge.

22:47.283 --> 22:49.285
<i>I'm confident that</i>
<i>the steel is hard,</i>

22:49.285 --> 22:52.329
<i>but my edge geometry</i>
<i>is not where it should be,</i>

22:52.329 --> 22:55.833
and I very seriously doubt
it will cut.

22:55.833 --> 22:58.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.919 --> 23:01.714
‐ Bladesmiths...to test
the strength and durability

23:01.714 --> 23:04.508
of your blades as well as
your overall construction,

23:04.508 --> 23:06.468
I'm gonna be bashing them
mercilessly

23:06.468 --> 23:07.720
into this anchor chain.

23:07.720 --> 23:09.513
<i>Remember, this test</i>
<i>is all about</i>

23:09.513 --> 23:10.890
what that chain does
to your knives

23:10.890 --> 23:12.349
and not what your knives
do to the chain.

23:12.349 --> 23:14.018
Jerad, you're up first.
You ready?

23:14.018 --> 23:15.853
‐ I'm ready.

23:15.853 --> 23:18.355
<i>I'm nervous as can be</i>
<i>right now.</i>

23:18.355 --> 23:20.274
<i>That chain is gonna be</i>
<i>brutal.</i>

23:20.274 --> 23:23.277
I don't know what to expect
when that chain gets hit.

23:23.277 --> 23:27.865
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:27.865 --> 23:30.868
[clinking]

23:30.868 --> 23:36.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:38.417 --> 23:39.710
[blade clatters]

23:39.710 --> 23:42.713
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

23:42.713 --> 23:44.965
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:44.965 --> 23:46.884
‐ Well, Jerad,
it's pretty evident

23:46.884 --> 23:48.719
what happened here.

23:48.719 --> 23:50.930
The one thing that
I talk about a lot

23:50.930 --> 23:52.556
are things called
stress risers.

23:52.556 --> 23:54.934
And where things rapidly
change geometry,

23:54.934 --> 23:57.269
it tends to concentrate stress
right there.

23:57.269 --> 24:00.773
And this broke right at
your very first saw tooth.

24:00.773 --> 24:02.775
<i>So, usually with saw teeth</i>
<i>like this</i>

24:02.775 --> 24:04.109
you wanna have
a curved bottom,

24:04.109 --> 24:06.737
'cause it kind of distributes
that stress.

24:06.737 --> 24:08.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:08.489 --> 24:09.698
‐ [sighs]

24:09.698 --> 24:13.285
Jerad, your blade has suffered
a catastrophic failure

24:13.285 --> 24:15.746
on the fifth strike
against this chain,

24:15.746 --> 24:17.915
and you can no longer continue
with testing.

24:17.915 --> 24:21.043
However, the fight's
not over for you.

24:21.043 --> 24:23.921
Each of you will have to
survive five strikes

24:23.921 --> 24:26.131
in order to move forward
in this competition.

24:26.131 --> 24:28.092
All right, then.

24:28.092 --> 24:30.469
‐ Lee, you've seen what
I'm up to.

24:30.469 --> 24:32.429
How you feeling?
‐ Pretty nervous.

24:32.429 --> 24:34.765
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:34.765 --> 24:36.934
<i>My blade's quite a bit wider.</i>

24:36.934 --> 24:39.645
<i>You know, the steel is</i>
<i>welded up good together,</i>

24:39.645 --> 24:43.440
<i>but that chain just destroyed</i>
<i>that blade.</i>

24:43.440 --> 24:46.193
<i>My stomach's just doing flips.</i>

24:46.193 --> 24:50.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:54.910 --> 24:56.662
[clangs]
‐ Ooh!

24:56.662 --> 24:59.289
‐ Oh, my God.

24:59.289 --> 25:02.209
‐ [sighs]

25:02.209 --> 25:06.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:06.171 --> 25:09.508
‐ Well, Lee, your grain
is beautiful.

25:09.508 --> 25:11.343
It's like velvet, you know.

25:11.343 --> 25:13.762
It should be
a very strong blade.

25:13.762 --> 25:17.182
The spot of the break, again,
is right at the base

25:17.182 --> 25:19.309
<i>of one of these saw teeth.</i>

25:19.309 --> 25:21.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:21.770 --> 25:24.982
‐ Lee, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

25:24.982 --> 25:28.527
after only one strike
on this anchor chain.

25:28.527 --> 25:32.197
Everything right now resides
on Elijah's blade.

25:32.197 --> 25:35.367
Your blade will have to
survive one strike

25:35.367 --> 25:37.036
on this anchor chain.

25:37.036 --> 25:39.663
Are you ready for this?
‐ No.

25:39.663 --> 25:41.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:41.582 --> 25:43.876
<i>I'm confident that</i>
<i>the steel is hard,</i>

25:43.876 --> 25:47.046
but Jerad and Lee's blades
just broke.

25:47.046 --> 25:48.797
Lee's, after one hit.

25:48.797 --> 25:51.717
It all comes down to my blade.

25:51.717 --> 25:54.887
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:54.887 --> 25:59.975
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:59.975 --> 26:02.394
‐ I can't see where
the hardened steel is.

26:02.394 --> 26:05.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:05.064 --> 26:07.775
Elijah, looking at the knife
that you presented here,

26:07.775 --> 26:09.109
there's a couple major issues.

26:09.109 --> 26:11.445
One is that this guard
is all over the place.

26:11.445 --> 26:14.865
But the one big issue I have
is that

26:14.865 --> 26:16.575
there's no acid etch
on this blade.

26:16.575 --> 26:18.243
‐ Yes, sir.

26:18.243 --> 26:21.246
‐ I can't tell on this side
where hardened steel is

26:21.246 --> 26:22.414
or soft steel is.

26:22.414 --> 26:23.749
I like to be able to see
where the steel is

26:23.749 --> 26:28.087
so that I can accurately judge
what you've done.

26:28.087 --> 26:31.924
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:31.924 --> 26:34.218
‐ Gentlemen, the parameters
exist so that

26:34.218 --> 26:36.678
we can measure your blades
evenly and fairly

26:36.678 --> 26:37.763
with one another.

26:37.763 --> 26:39.306
Elijah, you failed to meet
the parameters

26:39.306 --> 26:43.268
by failing to acid etch,
and your guard is loose.

26:43.268 --> 26:45.771
So the judges have given
your blade

26:45.771 --> 26:47.940
a vote of no confidence,
and I have to ask you

26:47.940 --> 26:49.274
to please leave The Forge.

26:49.274 --> 26:51.652
‐ I understand.
‐ Come forward, my friend.

26:51.652 --> 26:53.445
<i>‐ I'm an officer in</i>
<i>the United States Navy.</i>

26:53.445 --> 26:55.280
I'm about upholding
the rules.

26:55.280 --> 26:58.492
Thank you sir.
<i>And if I got to go forward,</i>

26:58.492 --> 26:59.827
it wouldn't have been right.

26:59.827 --> 27:01.120
Thank you, sir.
‐ Yeah.

27:01.120 --> 27:03.122
<i>‐ The first thing I'm gonna do</i>
<i>when I get home</i>

27:03.122 --> 27:05.040
is kiss my wife
and kiss my kids

27:05.040 --> 27:09.962
and forge a rubber stacked
Mark 3 dive knife

27:09.962 --> 27:11.964
<i>so that I can hang that</i>
<i>sucker up on the wall</i>

27:11.964 --> 27:14.967
<i>as a constant reminder</i>
<i>of attention to detail.</i>

27:14.967 --> 27:18.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:18.053 --> 27:19.721
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:19.721 --> 27:21.265
‐ Jerad, Lee, congratulations.

27:21.265 --> 27:23.642
You guys have made it into
the next phase of

27:23.642 --> 27:25.143
this selection process.

27:25.143 --> 27:27.479
What you're fighting for
is the navy anvil

27:27.479 --> 27:29.773
at the Battle of the Branches
final competition,

27:29.773 --> 27:32.317
and a chance to win $50,000.

27:32.317 --> 27:34.319
And now we're sending you back
to your home forges

27:34.319 --> 27:37.281
to recreate this
military weapon from history.

27:37.281 --> 27:40.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:40.492 --> 27:44.204
U.S. naval officer's sword.

27:44.204 --> 27:45.664
‐ Awesome.

27:45.664 --> 27:47.332
<i>‐ For over 250 years,</i>

27:47.332 --> 27:49.501
<i>the United States</i>
<i>naval officer sword has been</i>

27:49.501 --> 27:52.212
<i>a distinguished and integral</i>
<i>piece of uniform</i>

27:52.212 --> 27:53.714
<i>for navy personnel.</i>

27:53.714 --> 27:56.675
<i>Both ornate and functional,</i>
<i>the weapon is often engraved</i>

27:56.675 --> 27:58.510
<i>and features a lightweight</i>
<i>straight blade</i>

27:58.510 --> 28:01.513
<i>that was key for melee combat</i>
<i>onboard crowded vessels.</i>

28:01.513 --> 28:04.600
<i>Its sleek design was also</i>
<i>instrumental in defense,</i>

28:04.600 --> 28:07.019
<i>featuring a knuckle bow guard</i>
<i>to cover the hand.</i>

28:07.019 --> 28:08.854
<i>Although the officer's sword</i>
<i>underwent</i>

28:08.854 --> 28:11.023
<i>several design changes</i>
<i>and was eventually</i>

28:11.023 --> 28:12.858
<i>suspended from</i>
<i>combat operations,</i>

28:12.858 --> 28:14.359
<i>it is still worn in ceremonies</i>

28:14.359 --> 28:17.696
<i>as a symbol of</i>
<i>naval authority.</i>

28:17.696 --> 28:19.448
Make sure that your blades
fall within

28:19.448 --> 28:20.699
the following parameters:

28:20.699 --> 28:22.075
<i>the length of the blade</i>
<i>must be</i>

28:22.075 --> 28:23.869
<i>between 29 and 30 inches;</i>

28:23.869 --> 28:25.704
<i>you must have</i>
<i>a leaf‐shaped guard,</i>

28:25.704 --> 28:30.208
<i>upswept rear quillion,</i>
<i>knuckle bow, and pipe pommel.</i>

28:30.208 --> 28:32.794
<i>‐ It feels great to be</i>
<i>one step closer</i>

28:32.794 --> 28:34.630
to standing at that navy anvil.

28:34.630 --> 28:37.090
<i>Really excited about</i>
<i>the home build,</i>

28:37.090 --> 28:39.343
but it's gonna be a challenge.

28:39.343 --> 28:41.386
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

28:41.386 --> 28:43.138
in which to complete
all these parameters.

28:43.138 --> 28:44.556
At the end of those four days,

28:44.556 --> 28:46.099
you'll return and present
your blades to

28:46.099 --> 28:47.351
our panel of expert judges.

28:47.351 --> 28:49.895
After they've expertly
tested them,

28:49.895 --> 28:51.897
they'll push one of you
forward into

28:51.897 --> 28:54.191
the Battle of the Branches
competition.

28:54.191 --> 28:56.401
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

28:56.401 --> 28:58.612
‐ [exhales]

28:58.612 --> 29:01.615
<i>[rock music]</i>

29:01.615 --> 29:02.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:02.699 --> 29:04.159
‐ It's day one.

29:04.159 --> 29:06.244
<i>And the sword I'm making</i>
<i>for the challenge is</i>

29:06.244 --> 29:07.663
the naval officer sword.

29:07.663 --> 29:09.665
It's very intricate
and a lot of detail.

29:09.665 --> 29:11.083
[device whirs]

29:11.083 --> 29:12.876
<i>I'm not a sword guy,</i>

29:12.876 --> 29:16.254
so this is the longest sword
I've ever made.

29:16.254 --> 29:17.547
<i>Got it all heated up.</i>

29:17.547 --> 29:19.549
<i>You go to the power hammer,</i>
<i>flick it on,</i>

29:19.549 --> 29:22.636
step on the treadle,
and nothing.

29:22.636 --> 29:23.804
Oh, no.

29:23.804 --> 29:25.722
It's making noise,
but it's not moving.

29:25.722 --> 29:29.101
<i>So I have to do some</i>
<i>adjustments on the linkage,</i>

29:29.101 --> 29:30.268
<i>get it going.</i>

29:30.268 --> 29:31.436
I use this thing
and use this thing

29:31.436 --> 29:33.438
and use this thing,
and now it's not wanting

29:33.438 --> 29:34.773
to work right.

29:34.773 --> 29:36.942
With the time we're given,
with it only being four days,

29:36.942 --> 29:38.193
feeling a little bit of stress.

29:38.193 --> 29:39.861
[clanging]

29:39.861 --> 29:40.946
There we go.

29:40.946 --> 29:42.864
Now we're trucking.

29:42.864 --> 29:44.116
<i>This is a challenge.</i>

29:44.116 --> 29:46.326
It's hard, but it's still
a lot of fun.

29:46.326 --> 29:49.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:49.830 --> 29:51.999
<i>Today's day one and today</i>
<i>I'm working on</i>

29:51.999 --> 29:53.792
forging out the basic shape
of the sword

29:53.792 --> 29:56.253
<i>and maybe get to heat‐treat.</i>

29:56.253 --> 29:59.381
So, this navy officer sword's
very delicate.

29:59.381 --> 30:00.799
<i>It's intricate.</i>

30:00.799 --> 30:03.135
I think that's gonna be the
biggest part of this challenge.

30:03.135 --> 30:05.012
<i>In the previous rounds,</i>
<i>my knife broke,</i>

30:05.012 --> 30:07.139
<i>and so I wanna ensure that</i>
<i>I can make something</i>

30:07.139 --> 30:11.143
that's sturdy and will hold up
to any test that they have.

30:11.143 --> 30:13.645
Navy way is slow and smooth.

30:13.645 --> 30:15.897
<i>Start slow and it will</i>
<i>turn into</i>

30:15.897 --> 30:17.983
<i>speed and perfection later on.</i>

30:17.983 --> 30:21.153
I got my sword shaped out,
and I'm ready for a heat treat.

30:21.153 --> 30:24.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:24.990 --> 30:27.826
Into day one, no cracks.
I'm feeling pretty good.

30:27.826 --> 30:28.910
<i>I'm sitting well right now.</i>

30:28.910 --> 30:31.663
Yep, that is sexy.
All right.

30:31.663 --> 30:33.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:33.040 --> 30:35.709
‐ First thing I'm gonna do
today is use my rotary tool

30:35.709 --> 30:37.544
and hand‐grind in my fuller.

30:37.544 --> 30:39.504
[tool buzzing]

30:39.504 --> 30:40.672
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:40.672 --> 30:43.675
For a hand fuller,
you can't ask for much better.

30:43.675 --> 30:45.218
[clicks tongue]

30:45.218 --> 30:47.929
Blade's ready to be quenched.

30:47.929 --> 30:49.014
[device roaring]

30:49.014 --> 30:51.183
<i>The one think you always</i>
<i>think about is,</i>

30:51.183 --> 30:53.393
"Don't snap."
This is the moment.

30:53.393 --> 30:55.520
<i>"Don't have a warp."</i>
<i>Snaps are fatal.</i>

30:55.520 --> 30:57.355
Warps are critical,
they can be fixed.

30:57.355 --> 31:01.193
<i>[rock music]</i>

31:01.193 --> 31:03.445
Pull it out...

31:03.445 --> 31:06.698
Uh‐oh.
It's hard but it's got a bow.

31:06.698 --> 31:08.325
To the jig.

31:08.325 --> 31:10.035
<i>I have to get it in</i>
<i>my straightening jig</i>

31:10.035 --> 31:11.369
to see if we can get that
pulled down.

31:11.369 --> 31:12.704
Let's hope it straightened it.

31:12.704 --> 31:15.165
If not, we gotta go through
that whole thing again.

31:15.165 --> 31:18.251
Pick it up, look down it...bam.
We got a straight blade.

31:18.251 --> 31:22.047
"Ten minutes, bladesmiths.
You have ten tiny minutes."

31:22.047 --> 31:23.256
[laughs]

31:23.256 --> 31:24.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:24.382 --> 31:27.427
<i>‐ So, as of right now</i>
<i>my plan is to get</i>

31:27.427 --> 31:29.596
<i>some sheet steel,</i>
<i>use that for the majority</i>

31:29.596 --> 31:31.723
<i>of the leaf guard,</i>
<i>and then getting some steel</i>

31:31.723 --> 31:33.642
<i>for the knuckle guard</i>
<i>and braiding it.</i>

31:33.642 --> 31:36.728
Kind of give it a nautical,
naval theme to it.

31:36.728 --> 31:39.981
<i>Try and make it look like</i>
<i>some rope or line.</i>

31:39.981 --> 31:41.399
[clanging]

31:41.399 --> 31:45.320
This wire's bulking up way more
than I thought it would be.

31:45.320 --> 31:46.822
I'm trying to braid this thing.

31:46.822 --> 31:48.990
It's not moving the way
I want it to.

31:48.990 --> 31:51.993
<i>I didn't want nearly as many</i>
<i>gaps as this,</i>

31:51.993 --> 31:54.371
so I'm starting to get
a little frustrated.

31:54.371 --> 31:56.248
<i>I still have</i>
<i>a whole lot to do.</i>

31:56.248 --> 31:58.291
<i>But at the end of the day,</i>
<i>I'm treating this as if</i>

31:58.291 --> 32:00.043
<i>this is a $50,000 sword,</i>

32:00.043 --> 32:03.213
so I'm gonna put every ounce
of energy I have into it.

32:03.213 --> 32:05.507
I decided I'm just gonna stick
this in the vice

32:05.507 --> 32:09.177
<i>and start twisting</i>
<i>until it looks like rope.</i>

32:09.177 --> 32:11.471
All right.

32:11.471 --> 32:14.266
<i>‐ First things first‐‐</i>
<i>put the coffee down,</i>

32:14.266 --> 32:15.559
pick the sword up.

32:15.559 --> 32:19.437
Tempered last night, and the
warp I thought I had fixed

32:19.437 --> 32:20.939
came back in the temper
overnight.

32:20.939 --> 32:24.109
Right down the edge,
right on that spine.

32:24.109 --> 32:26.778
I have to get this fixed before
I move on with the sword.

32:26.778 --> 32:28.155
[groans]

32:28.155 --> 32:32.117
To get this warp out,
I'm gonna have to pin it...

32:32.117 --> 32:34.327
<i>heat up the spin,</i>
<i>then let it relax,</i>

32:34.327 --> 32:36.413
and hopefully the warp
will come out.

32:36.413 --> 32:38.498
We're not turning in
a bent blade.

32:38.498 --> 32:40.333
<i>The danger with heating</i>
<i>this blade up is</i>

32:40.333 --> 32:42.836
you pull the hardness
out of the metal,

32:42.836 --> 32:44.504
and you have to re‐quench
again.

32:44.504 --> 32:47.048
<i>And that could</i>
<i>set me back hours.</i>

32:47.048 --> 32:48.466
It would be crushing.
Fingers crossed.

32:51.887 --> 32:53.680
[tapping]

32:53.680 --> 32:55.807
A little tap,
but I can live with that.

32:55.807 --> 32:56.808
It don't rock.

32:56.808 --> 32:59.644
To finally get this warp out...

32:59.644 --> 33:00.812
Still hard.

33:00.812 --> 33:03.148
Now I can move forward.
What a load off.

33:03.148 --> 33:04.191
All right.

33:04.191 --> 33:06.651
It's time to move on to
the handle material.

33:06.651 --> 33:09.487
<i>I set up the Micarta handles</i>
<i>by cutting them rough shape</i>

33:09.487 --> 33:12.991
to fit the handle...
drill the holes.

33:12.991 --> 33:14.159
Like that!

33:14.159 --> 33:15.952
<i>I think I need to get</i>
<i>the pommel,</i>

33:15.952 --> 33:18.830
so when I do make the guard
and knuckle bow,

33:18.830 --> 33:21.333
I know where to end it.
So I need the pommel next.

33:21.333 --> 33:22.876
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:22.876 --> 33:24.336
<i>It's pretty blade‐heavy</i>

33:24.336 --> 33:26.630
and it's going to need
a big chunk of brass

33:26.630 --> 33:28.048
to be able to balance
that out.

33:28.048 --> 33:29.507
Done. [laughs]

33:29.507 --> 33:30.842
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:30.842 --> 33:32.594
<i>‐ Today's day four.</i>

33:32.594 --> 33:35.138
All I really got to do is put
these pieces together,

33:35.138 --> 33:38.683
put some epoxy in the handle,
polish, and sharpen.

33:40.143 --> 33:43.146
<i>I came here to prove to myself</i>
<i>that I have what it takes</i>

33:43.146 --> 33:45.690
to take on bladesmithing
full‐time

33:45.690 --> 33:47.192
once I retire from the navy.

33:47.192 --> 33:49.027
<i>Regardless of how this</i>
<i>goes down,</i>

33:49.027 --> 33:51.279
<i>I proved that to myself</i>
<i>during this build.</i>

33:51.279 --> 33:52.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:52.906 --> 33:55.075
‐ Lee, Jerad,
welcome back to The Forge.

33:55.075 --> 33:57.535
You sailors had four days
at your home forges

33:57.535 --> 34:00.538
to work on your
naval officer swords.

34:00.538 --> 34:01.581
Lee, how did it go?

34:01.581 --> 34:03.041
‐ It went good.
Had a couple of hiccups.

34:03.041 --> 34:05.877
But overall, it was a really
challenging, fun build.

34:05.877 --> 34:08.213
<i>It's a 1084 steel blade,</i>

34:08.213 --> 34:11.216
<i>linen Micarta core handle</i>
<i>wrapped in white leather.</i>

34:11.216 --> 34:13.218
<i>Gold wire wrap,</i>
<i>solid brass pummel,</i>

34:13.218 --> 34:15.887
<i>and hand‐hammered brass guard.</i>

34:15.887 --> 34:17.514
‐ All right, Jerad,
how did it go for you?

34:17.514 --> 34:19.391
‐ Uh, it went well.
It was a fun build.

34:19.391 --> 34:22.060
<i>The blade itself is 1080.</i>

34:22.060 --> 34:24.104
<i>The whole guard assembly</i>
<i>is mild steel</i>

34:24.104 --> 34:25.897
<i>with a, uh, brass transfer</i>
<i>over it.</i>

34:25.897 --> 34:29.276
<i>Uh, handle is Amboyna burl</i>
<i>with a wire wrap.</i>

34:29.276 --> 34:30.402
‐ All right, gentlemen,

34:30.402 --> 34:31.903
now that your blades
have been turned in,

34:31.903 --> 34:33.363
it's time to test them.

34:33.363 --> 34:35.490
Now first, the KEAL test.
Doug?

34:35.490 --> 34:37.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:37.200 --> 34:40.078
‐ All right, sailors,
your weapons look beautiful.

34:40.078 --> 34:42.205
But it's time to find out
if they're wall hangers

34:42.205 --> 34:45.250
or they're actually something
you can use to KEAL.

34:45.250 --> 34:47.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:47.419 --> 34:49.087
Jerad, you're up first.
You ready for this?

34:49.087 --> 34:51.256
‐ I'm ready.
‐ Let's do this.

34:51.256 --> 34:53.883
<i>‐ I'm nervous.</i>
<i>They're going to be slicing</i>

34:53.883 --> 34:55.051
and dicing up this pig.

34:55.051 --> 34:58.555
I'm just scared
of that spine on the pig.

34:58.555 --> 35:01.766
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:01.766 --> 35:08.898
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:13.820 --> 35:16.656
‐ [chuckles]

35:16.656 --> 35:17.949
‐ All right, Jerad,

35:17.949 --> 35:20.952
the balance you have here
feels good in the hand.

35:20.952 --> 35:22.954
Now, your edge is very sharp.

35:22.954 --> 35:25.624
As you can see,
with every cut, it cuts deep.

35:25.624 --> 35:28.501
For every thrust,
all the way through and true.

35:28.501 --> 35:31.963
Overall, sir,
your weapon will KEAL.

35:31.963 --> 35:33.673
‐ Thank you.
‐ Good job.

35:33.673 --> 35:36.134
All right, Lee,
it's your turn. You ready?

35:36.134 --> 35:38.637
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Let's do this.

35:38.637 --> 35:42.307
‐ That's a lot of hog to go
through with a skinny blade.

35:42.307 --> 35:44.684
I'm pretty nervous.

35:44.684 --> 35:47.979
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:47.979 --> 35:53.485
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:02.619 --> 36:04.871
‐ Good job.
‐ Thanks.

36:04.871 --> 36:06.623
‐ All right, Lee.

36:06.623 --> 36:08.875
The handle construction
is comfortable.

36:08.875 --> 36:13.713
Your edge? Not one
single glint or rolling.

36:13.713 --> 36:17.467
Your tip punctures
and cuts on the way out.

36:17.467 --> 36:20.303
And overall, sir,
it will KEAL.

36:20.303 --> 36:21.846
‐ Yes!

36:21.846 --> 36:24.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:24.182 --> 36:26.893
‐ All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the strength test.

36:26.893 --> 36:29.521
The dreaded flex test.

36:29.521 --> 36:31.690
To test the strength
of your blade,

36:31.690 --> 36:34.067
I'll be bending it
in both directions

36:34.067 --> 36:36.528
up to that red point.

36:36.528 --> 36:38.530
Jerad, you ready for this?
‐ I guess.

36:38.530 --> 36:40.156
‐ Okay.

36:41.866 --> 36:43.034
‐ [sighs]

36:43.034 --> 36:46.371
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

36:46.371 --> 36:53.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:53.169 --> 36:54.546
[groans]

36:54.546 --> 36:55.880
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:55.880 --> 36:58.383
Ooh! [chuckles]

36:58.383 --> 37:05.348
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:07.350 --> 37:09.769
[sighs deeply]

37:09.769 --> 37:11.730
‐ I'm impressed.

37:11.730 --> 37:14.441
Uh, your blade is just
as straight

37:14.441 --> 37:16.401
as when we started the test.

37:16.401 --> 37:18.236
That's a really nice
heat treat.

37:18.236 --> 37:19.571
‐ Thank you.

37:19.571 --> 37:20.822
‐ Holding your sword.

37:20.822 --> 37:23.408
You can shorten that handle
just a little bit scale‐wise.

37:23.408 --> 37:26.453
But at the same time, it winds
up being fairly comfortable.

37:26.453 --> 37:28.121
Nicely done.
‐ Thanks.

37:28.121 --> 37:30.290
All right, Lee, you're up.
You ready for this?

37:30.290 --> 37:31.916
‐ Yes, sir.
‐ Okay.

37:31.916 --> 37:34.878
<i>‐ My heart is just pounding.</i>

37:34.878 --> 37:37.547
<i>God, I hope I did</i>
<i>my heat treat right</i>

37:37.547 --> 37:40.091
to where I can take the bend
and come back to true.

37:40.091 --> 37:43.261
<i>This is really what is really</i>
<i>gonna push our blades.</i>

37:43.261 --> 37:46.765
Can my blade take a bend
and not snap?

37:46.765 --> 37:47.724
<i>[intensifying music]</i>

37:51.478 --> 37:57.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:57.400 --> 38:00.528
<i>The longest five seconds</i>
<i>of my life,</i>

38:00.528 --> 38:02.697
<i>but I'm holding my breath</i>

38:02.697 --> 38:05.700
just praying that
it holds together.

38:05.700 --> 38:11.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:18.004 --> 38:19.631
[sighs]

38:19.631 --> 38:20.924
‐ Nice job, Lee.

38:20.924 --> 38:23.510
Your blade is still the same
shape that it started at.

38:23.510 --> 38:25.094
That's impressive.
‐ Thank you, sir.

38:25.094 --> 38:26.846
‐ Really good.

38:26.846 --> 38:29.474
All right, gentlemen, it's
time for the sharpness test.

38:29.474 --> 38:31.643
We call this the Fish Slice.

38:31.643 --> 38:33.353
We're going to be lowering
those fish down.

38:33.353 --> 38:34.687
I'm just gonna start cutting.

38:34.687 --> 38:36.564
I'm gonna keep cutting
until I run out of fish.

38:36.564 --> 38:38.107
All right, Jerad,
you're up first.

38:38.107 --> 38:39.359
Are you ready?
‐ I'm ready.

38:39.359 --> 38:45.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:55.250 --> 38:56.376
‐ [chuckles]

38:56.376 --> 38:57.710
This is why I love sabers.

38:57.710 --> 39:00.004
They are just so much fun
to cut with.

39:00.004 --> 39:03.424
It's just passing right
through the fish beautifully.

39:03.424 --> 39:06.845
Your handle construction
might be a little bit wide,

39:06.845 --> 39:08.847
but it's comfortable,
and it stays in my hand.

39:08.847 --> 39:11.641
I think you did a great job.
‐ Thank you.

39:11.641 --> 39:13.726
Lee? You ready?

39:13.726 --> 39:15.770
‐ [sighs] Yes, sir.
‐ [chuckles] Okay.

39:15.770 --> 39:21.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:32.161 --> 39:34.747
All right, Lee,
it cuts beautifully.

39:34.747 --> 39:37.750
I mean, the edge
on this is wonderful.

39:37.750 --> 39:40.628
Saber's definitely sharp
and a great balance.

39:40.628 --> 39:42.630
Nicely done.
‐ Thank you, sir.

39:42.630 --> 39:44.048
<i>Jerad and I are neck and neck.</i>

39:44.048 --> 39:46.759
I mean, both blades
performed great.

39:46.759 --> 39:49.512
‐ Jerad, Lee, only one of you
can move forward

39:49.512 --> 39:51.598
and that smith is...

39:51.598 --> 39:56.644
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

39:56.644 --> 39:58.771
Lee, congratulations.

39:58.771 --> 40:00.607
You'll be moving forward
to represent

40:00.607 --> 40:01.774
the United States Navy

40:01.774 --> 40:03.943
in the Battle of the Branches
final competition.

40:03.943 --> 40:05.945
Congratulations. Good job.
‐ Thank you.

40:05.945 --> 40:09.616
Jerad, unfortunately,
your blade didn't make the cut

40:09.616 --> 40:11.367
and David Baker's
gonna tell you why.

40:11.367 --> 40:14.120
‐ Jerad, you brought us
an effective cutting sword.

40:14.120 --> 40:16.456
But this came down
to the basic details

40:16.456 --> 40:20.043
of aesthetics and the way
that weapon felt in my hand.

40:20.043 --> 40:21.169
‐ I understand.

40:21.169 --> 40:24.130
‐ Well, Jerad,
come on forward, brother.

40:24.130 --> 40:25.548
Good job.

40:25.548 --> 40:29.469
<i>‐ This competition was such</i>
<i>a learning experience for me.</i>

40:29.469 --> 40:31.971
<i>Uh, made a lot</i>
<i>of good friends.</i>

40:31.971 --> 40:33.139
I had a great time.

40:33.139 --> 40:34.766
Give them hell.
‐ Good job, shipmate.

40:34.766 --> 40:38.394
‐ I didn't win but I did two,
uh, very awesome swords.

40:38.394 --> 40:40.104
<i>Lee, you did well.</i>

40:40.104 --> 40:42.649
Give them hell and
take it home for the navy.

40:42.649 --> 40:44.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:44.108 --> 40:45.360
‐ Lee, congratulations,

40:45.360 --> 40:47.528
<i>you forged your way into</i>
<i>this final competition</i>

40:47.528 --> 40:48.696
<i>where you'll compete against</i>

40:48.696 --> 40:49.948
<i>the Air Force, Army,</i>

40:49.948 --> 40:50.949
<i>and Marine Corps</i>

40:50.949 --> 40:51.950
<i>to bring home the title</i>

40:51.950 --> 40:53.618
of Forged in Fire champion

40:53.618 --> 40:55.078
to the United States Navy.

40:55.078 --> 40:59.832
And you'll also be competing
to receive a check for $50,000.

40:59.832 --> 41:01.501
You've done a fantastic job.

41:01.501 --> 41:03.169
You're only halfway there.

41:03.169 --> 41:04.545
We'll see you real soon.

41:04.545 --> 41:06.047
Good job.
‐ Thank you, sir.

41:06.047 --> 41:09.842
I just won.
Really? Really? Really?

41:09.842 --> 41:13.638
<i>Being able to represent</i>
<i>the navy is an honor.</i>

41:13.638 --> 41:15.640
I am totally ready to do
this all over again.

41:15.640 --> 41:17.642
<i>And I'm gonna tell you guys</i>
<i>to bring your A‐game</i>

41:17.642 --> 41:19.143
because I'm bringing mine.

41:19.143 --> 41:24.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>
